<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
<worksheet xml:id="activity-01-intro-activity">
  <title>Studypalooza, Spring 2026</title>

  <!-- Optional introduction -->
  <introduction>
    <p>
      There are 50 problems for the Studypalooza event for Reading Day in Spring 2026.  
      They were compiled using PreTeXt with the specific intention of producing a PDF 
      that meets the WCAG 2.0 accessibility guidelines.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- Exercises start here. -->
  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        True or false: If <m>\{u, v, w\}</m> is a set of linearly dependent vectors, then <m>w</m> must be
a linear combination of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>   
  <solution>
    <p>
       False.  For example, in <m>{\bf R}^2</m> take
        <m>u = v = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0  \end{pmatrix}</m>
        and <m>w = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the value of <m>k</m> that makes the following vectors linearly dependent:
        <m>\displaystyle
          \left\{
            \begin{pmatrix}
          -3 \\ 0 \\ 3
        \end{pmatrix},
        \begin{pmatrix}
         3 \\ -3 \\ k
        \end{pmatrix},
        \begin{pmatrix}
        3 \\ -1 \\ -1
        \end{pmatrix}
        \right\}.
        </m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <p>
        Take the matrix <m>A</m> whose columns are the vectors and row-reduce a
        bit:
        <p>
        <m> \displaystyle
        A = \begin{pmatrix} -3 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -3 \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp k \amp -1
            \end{pmatrix}
        \rightarrow
        \begin{pmatrix} -3 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -3 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp k+3 \amp 2  \end{pmatrix}
        </m>
        </p>
        This matrix will have three pivots unless
        the second and third rows are multiples of each other.  This means the
        third row is <m>-2</m> times the second, so <m>-3(-2) = k+3</m>, hence
        <m>k=3</m>.  Alternatively, the student could have computed <m>\det(A) =
        9 - 3k</m>, so <m>k=3</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>


   <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        True or false: If <m>\{u, v\}</m> is a basis for a subspace <m>W</m>, then
        <m>\{u-v, u+v\}</m> is also a basis for <m>W</m>.        
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>    

  <solution>
    <p>
        <p> True. By the Basis Theorem, any two linearly independent vectors in <m>V</m>
        will form a basis for <m>V</m>, so we just need to show
        <m>\{u-v, u+v\}</m> is linearly independent.  For this, suppose
        <md>x_1(u-v) + x_2(u+v) = 0</md>.  We expand and find
        <md>(x_1+x_2)u + (x_2-x_1)v = 0</md>.     
        </p>
        <p>
        Since <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are linearly independent, this requires
        <m>x_1 + x_2 = 0</m> and <m>x_2-x_1 =0</m>, which is only satisfied
        when <m>x_1 = x_2 = 0</m>.  
        </p>
        <p>
        This shows that the vector equation <m>x_1(u-v) + x_2(u+v) = 0</m> has
        only the trivial solution <m>x_1 = x_2 = 0</m>, so <m>\{u-v, u+v\}</m>
        is linearly independent.    
        </p>    
    </p>
  </solution>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Which of the following are subspaces of <m>{\bf R}^4</m>?
        <ol>
        <li>The set
        <m>W = \left\{ \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \\ w  \end{pmatrix} \
        \mathrm{ in } \ {\bf R}^{4} \ \Big| \ 2x - y - z = 0\right\}</m></li>
        <li>The set of solutions to
        <m> 
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp -1
        \end{pmatrix} x
        =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 \\ 0
        \end{pmatrix}
        </m>
        </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>    
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol>
      <li>Yes, <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>{\bf R}^4</m> since it is
      <m>\mathrm{Nul}\begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      <li>No, it is not a subspace.  In fact, it fails the very first property of subspaces
        since it does not contain
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
      <p>
      True or false: The set <m>W</m> of vectors
      <m> \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c  \end{pmatrix}</m> with <m>abc = 0</m>. Then
      <m>W</m> is closed under addition.
       </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

    <solution>
    <p> False.  For example, the vectors <m>u = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0  \end{pmatrix}</m>
    and <m>v = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}</m> are in <m>W</m>, but
    <m>u+v = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}</m> which is not in <m>W</m>
    since <m>1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \neq 0</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>

  <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
     <p>
      Write the matrices for each of the following.  
      <ol>
      <li>Counterclockwise rotation by <m>90^\circ</m>.</li>
      <li>Reflection across the line <m>y = x</m>.</li>
      <li>Clockwise rotation by <m>90^\circ</m></li>
      <li>Reflection across the <m>x</m>-axis.</li>
      <li>Reflection across the <m>y</m>-axis.</li>
      </ol>
     </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

    <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
      <li>Counterclockwise rotation by <m>90^\circ</m>:
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0  \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      <li>Reflection across the line <m>y = x</m>:
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0  \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      <li>Clockwise rotation by <m>90^\circ</m>:
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0  \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      <li>Reflection across the <m>x</m>-axis:
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
      <li>Reflection across the <m>y</m>-axis:
      <m>\begin{pmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1  \end{pmatrix}</m>.</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Find all <m>k</m> so that <m>\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}</m>
    and <m> \begin{pmatrix} k \\ 1 \\ -6  \end{pmatrix} </m> are orthogonal.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    We set <m>0 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k \\ 1  \end{pmatrix} \cdot
    \begin{pmatrix} k \\ 1 \\ -6  \end{pmatrix} = 2k+k-6</m>, so <m>k = 2</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Find all <m>k</m> so that the matrix transformation corresponding to the following
    matrix is not onto:
    <m> \displaystyle
      \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp 9 \\ 2 \amp 6 \amp k  \end{pmatrix}.
    </m>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    The columns of the matrix will span <m>${\bf R}^{2}$</m> unless they are all
    collinear, in which case <m>k = 18</m>.  Alternatively, we could find <m>k</m>
    by row-reducing and determining when the matrix will fail to have a pivot in the
    second row.
    </p>
    </solution>   
    
    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>T: {\bf R}^a \to {\bf R}^b</m> be a transformation.      
    Match the four statements with their corresponding terms listed below.
    <ol>
    <li>For each <m>y</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{b}</m>, there is at most
    one <m>x</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{a} </m> so that <m>T(x) = y</m>.</li>
    <li>For each <m>y</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{b}</m>, there is at least
    one <m>x</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{a} </m> so that <m>T(x) = y</m>.</li>
    <li>For each <m>y</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{b}</m>, there is at exactly
    one <m>x</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{a} </m> so that <m>T(x) = y</m>.</li>
    <li>For each <m>x</m> in <m> {\bf R}^{a}</m>, there is exactly
    one <m>y</m> in <m>{\bf R}^{b}</m> so that <m>T(x) = y</m>.</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    <p>The terms are: "transformation," "one-to-one," "onto," and "invertible."</p> 
    </statement>
    </exercise>      
    <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>One-to-one, directly from the definition.  This says that any <m>y</m>
    in the codomain of <m>T</m> is the image of at most one <m>x</m>
    in the domain.</li>
    <li>Onto, directly from the definition.</li>
    <li>Invertible: this statement says <m>T</m> is one-to-one and onto.</li>
    <li>Transformation, directly from the definition.</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    True or false: Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>4 \times 6</m> matrix.  Then the
    dimension of the null space of <m>A</m> is at most <m>2</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    False.  Just take <m>A</m> to be the <m>4 \times 6</m> zero matrix, then
    its null space has dimension <m>6</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>


    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Complete the entries of <m>A</m> so that <m>\textrm{Col}(A)
    = \textrm{Span}\left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2  \end{pmatrix}\right\}</m>
    and
    <m>\textrm{Nul}(A)
    = \textrm{Span}\left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}\right\}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
    <m>\displaystyle A = \begin{pmatrix} r \amp 1 \\ s \amp 2  \end{pmatrix}.</m>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    For <m>\textrm{Col}(A)</m> to be the desired line,
    <m>\begin{pmatrix}  r \\ s\end{pmatrix}</m> must be a scalar multiple of
     <m>\begin{pmatrix}  1 \\ 2\end{pmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
     We also need
     <m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix}</m> to be in the null space of
     <m>A</m>, and solving <m>A \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1  \end{pmatrix} =
     \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0  \end{pmatrix}</m> gives us <m>r+1 = 0</m>
     and <m>s+2 = 0</m>, so <m>r = -1</m> and <m>s = -2</m>.                             
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>T: {\bf R}^7 \to {\bf R}^9</m> is a linear transformation with
    standard matrix <m>A</m>, and suppose the range of <m>T</m> has a
    basis consisting of <m>3</m> vectors.  What is the nullity of <m>A</m>?
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    We are given that the dimension of the range of <m>T</m> is <m>3</m>,
    which means that the rank of <m>A</m> is <m>3</m>.  From the codomain
    and domain of <m>T</m>, we know that <m>A</m> is a <m>9 \times 7</m>
    matrix.  By the Rank Theorem:
    <m>\displaystyle
    \textrm{nullity}(A) = 7 - \textrm{rank}(A)
    = 7 - 3 = 4</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Define <m>T: {\bf R}^3 \to {\bf R}^4</m> by
    <m>T(x,y,z) = (0, x-y, y-x, z)</m>. </p>
    <p>Is <m>T</m> one-to-one? Is <m>T</m> onto?
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    No, <m>T</m> is not one-to-one.  One way to see this is that the equation
    <m>T(v) = 0</m> has infinitely many solutions, since for any real number
    <m>c</m> we get
    <m>T(c, c, 0) = (0, c-c, c-c, 0) = (0, 0, 0, 0)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
    Also, <m>T</m> is not onto: every vector in the range of <m>T</m> has
    <m>0</m> as its first entry, so for example <m>(1, 0, 0, 0)</m> is not in
    the range of <m>T</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>7 \times 5</m> matrix and its null space is
    a line, and let <m>T</m> be the matrix transformation <m>T(x) = Ax</m>.
    What is true about the range of <m>T</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>It is a <m>4</m>-dimensional subspace of <m>{\bf R}^5</m>.</li>
    <li>It is a <m>6</m>-dimensional subspace of <m>{\bf R}^7</m>.</li>
    <li>It is a <m>4</m>-dimensional subspace of <m>{\bf R}^7</m>.</li>
    <li>It is a <m>6</m>-dimensional subspace of <m>{\bf R}^5</m>.</li>
    <li>none of these</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    Since <m>A</m> is <m>7 \times 5</m>, we know its column space is a subspace
    of <m>{\bf R}^7</m>.  From the fact that the null space of <m>A</m> is a
    line, we have <m>\textrm{rank}(A) = 5-1=4</m> by the Rank Theorem, so
    the column space of <m>A</m> is <m>4</m>-dimensional.</p>
    <p>
    Since the range of <m>T</m>
    is the column space of <m>A</m>, this means that the range of <m>T</m>
    is a <m>4</m>-dimensional subspace of <m>{\bf R}^7</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Say that <m>S: {\bf R}^2 \to {\bf R}^3</m> and
    <m>T: {\bf R}^3 \to {\bf R}^4</m> are linear transformations.  Which one of the
    following must be true about <m>T \circ S</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>It is one-to-one</li>
    <li>It is not one-to-one</li>
    <li>It is onto</li>
    <li>The composition <m>T \circ S</m> is not defined</li>
    <li>It is not onto</li>    
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    The transformation <m>T \circ S</m> might be one-to-one.  For example,
    if <m>S(x, y) = (x, y, 0)</m> and <m>T(x,y,z) = (x,y,z,0)</m>, then
    <m>(T \circ S)(x, y) = (x, y, 0, 0)</m>, so this particular <m>T \circ S</m> is
    one-to-one.
    </p>
    <p>
    However, <m>T \circ S</m> cannot be onto because it corresponds to
    multiplication by a <m>4 \times 2</m> matrix, which has a max of <m>2</m>
    pivots and therefore cannot have a pivot in every row.
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    True or false: Suppose that <m>A</m> is an invertible <m>n \times n</m>
    matrix.  Then <m>A+A</m> must be invertible.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    True, since <m>(2A)^{-1} = \dfrac{1}{2} A^{-1}</m>.  To confirm this, we can 
    compute
    <m>(2A)\left(\dfrac{1}{2} A^{-1}\right) = \left(2 \cdot \dfrac{1}{2}\right)
    AA^{-1} = I</m>, and similarly <m>\left(\dfrac{1}{2} A^{-1}\right)(2A) = I</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>  
    
    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    True or false: Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix and the equation
    <m>Ax = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \\ 2  \end{pmatrix}</m> has exactly one solution.
    Then <m>A</m> must be invertible.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    True. Since <m>Ax = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \\ 2  \end{pmatrix}</m> has
    exactly one solution, we conclude <m>A</m> has a pivot in every column, so 
    <m>A</m> is invertible by the Invertible Matrix Theorem.
    </p>
    </solution>

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices and
    <m>AB</m> is not invertible.  Which one of the following must be true?
    <ol>
    <li><m>A</m> is not invertible.</li>
    <li><m>B</m> is not invertible.</li>
    <li>At least one of the matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is not
    invertible.</li>
    <li>none of these.</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    At least one of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is not invertible. One way to
    see this is through the formula for the determinant.  Since <m>AB</m>
    is not invertible, we know <m>0 = \det(AB) = \det(A) \det(B)</m>, so
    it must be true that <m>\det(A) = 0</m> or <m>\det(B) = 0</m> (or both).
    </p>
    <p>
    We cannot conclude that <m>A</m> is the one that must not be invertible,
    or that <m>B</m> is the one that must not be invertible.  For example,
    it could be the case that <m>A=I</m> and <m>B = 0</m>, or that
    <m>A = 0</m> and <m>B = I</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>3 \times 3</m> matrices,
    with <m>\det(A) = 3</m> and <m>\det(B) = -6</m>.  Find
    <m>\det(2A^{-1}B)</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    Multiplying a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix by <m>2</m> will multiply each row
    of the matrix by <m>2</m>, so it will multiply the determinant by 
    <m>8</m>.   
    </p>
    <p>
    Using this fact and the properties of the determinant, we compute
    <m>\displaystyle
    \det(2A^{-1}B) = 8 \det(A^{-1}B) = 8 \det(A^{-1}) \det(B)
    = 8 \cdot \dfrac{1}{3} \cdot (-6) = -16.
    </m>
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>A</m> be the <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix satisfying
    <m>A e_1 = e_3</m>, <m>A e_2 = e_2</m>, and <m>A e_3 = 2e_1</m>
    (recall that <m>e_1</m>, <m>e_2</m>, and <m>e_3</m> are the standard
    basis vectors of <m>{\bf R}^3</m>).
    </p> 
    <p>
    Find <m>\det(A)</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    <m>A = \begin{pmatrix} A e_1 \amp A e_2 \amp A e_3  \end{pmatrix} </m>,
    so
    <m>\det(A) = \det \begin{pmatrix}
                        0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
                        0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                        1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
                      = -2.
    </m>
    </p>
    </solution>   
    
    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> is a square matrix and <m>\lambda = -1</m> is an
    eigenvalue of <m>A</m>.  Which one of the following must be true?
    <ol>
    <li><m>\textrm{Nul}(A+I) = \left\{0\right\}.</m></li>
    <li><m>A</m> is invertible. </li>    
    <li>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</li>
    <li>For some nonzero vector <m>x</m>, the vectors <m>Ax</m>
    and <m>x</m> are linearly dependent.</li>
    <li>The equation <m>Ax = x</m> has only the trivial solution.</li>    
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>Not true, in fact <m>\textrm{Nul}(A+I)</m> must have dimension
    at least <m>1</m> since <m>\lambda = -1</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>.
    </li>
    <li>Not necessarily true.  For example,
    <m>A = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\  0 \amp 0\end{pmatrix}</m>
    is not invertible even though it has <m>\lambda = -1</m> as an eigenvalue.
    </li>
    <li>Not necessarily true.  For example, if
    <m>A = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\  0 \amp 0\end{pmatrix}</m>,
    then <m>\lambda = -1</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>, but the
    columns of <m>A</m> are not linearly independent.
    </li>
    <li>True: for any nonzero vector in the <m>(-1)</m>-eigenspace of <m>A</m>,
    we have <m>Ax = -x</m>, so
    <m>\left\{Ax, x\right\}</m> is a  linearly dependent set.
    </li>
    <li>Not necessarily true.  For example, if
    <m>A = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\  0 \amp 1\end{pmatrix}</m>
    then <m>\lambda = -1</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>, but the
    equation <m>Ax = x</m> has infinitely many solutions since
    <m>\lambda = 1</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>.
    </li>    
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>
    
    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix with characteristic
    polynomial <m> -\lambda(1-\lambda)^2(5-\lambda).</m>
    </p>
    <p>
    What is the rank of <m>A</m>?
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    From the characteristic polynomial of <m>A</m>, we see that
    <m>\lambda = 0</m> is an eigenvalue of <m>A</m> with algebraic multiplicity
    <m>1</m>, so its geometric multiplicity must also be <m>1</m>.  In other
    words, the <m>0</m>-eigenspace is <m>1</m>-dimensional.  
    </p>
    <p>
    Therefore,
    <m>\textrm{rank}(A) = 4-1 = 3</m>.
    </p>
    </solution> 

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>T: {\bf R}^2 \to {\bf R}^2</m> be the linear transformation that
    reflects across the line <m>x_2 = 2x_1</m>.  Find the value of <m>k</m>
    so that <m>T \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k  \end{pmatrix}
    = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k  \end{pmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    Recall that for any <m>2 \times 2</m> reflection matrix <m>A</m>, the line
    of reflection is the <m>1</m>-eigenspace of <m>A</m>.  In other words,
    <m>Ax = x</m> for every <m>x</m> on the line of reflection.
    Here, the standard matrix for <m>T</m> is the matrix <m>A</m> that
    reflects vectors across <m>x_2 = 2x_1</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
    Therefore, to solve <m>T \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k  \end{pmatrix} =
    \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k  \end{pmatrix}</m>, we need
    <m> \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ k  \end{pmatrix} </m> to be on the line
    <m>x_2 = 2x_1</m>.  Thus <m>k = 2(2) = 4.</m>
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Find the value of <m>k</m> so that
    <m> \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp k \\ 1 \amp 3  \end{pmatrix} </m>
    has one real eigenvalue with algebraic multiplicity <m>2</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    The characteristic polynomial of the matrix is
    <m>\displaystyle (1-\lambda)(3-\lambda)-k
    = \lambda^2 - 4\lambda + 3 - k = (\lambda-2)^2-1-k.</m>
    </p>
    <p>
    For this polynomial to have only one real root with algebraic multiplicity
    <m>2</m>, it must be a perfect square, so <m> -1-k = 0</m>,
    thus <m>k = -1</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>    
 

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Suppose <m>A</m> is a diagonalizable matrix with characteristic polynomial
    <m>\det(A-\lambda I) = (1-\lambda)^3(2-\lambda)(3-\lambda).</m>    
    </p>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>What is the dimension of the <m>1</m>-eigenspace of <m>A</m>?</li>
    <li>For some <m>n</m>, the <m>1</m>-eigenspace of <m>A</m> is a subspace
    of <m>{\bf R}^n</m>.  What is <m>n</m>?</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
    <li>Since <m>A</m> is diagonalizable and the eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 1</m> has
    algebraic multiplicity <m>3</m>, the dimension of the <m>1</m>-eigenspace
    must also equal <m>3</m>.</li>
    <li> The characteristic polynomial of <m>A</m> has degree <m>5</m>, so the
    matrix <m>A</m> must be <m>5 \times 5</m>.  This means the
    <m>1</m>-eigenspace of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <m>{\bf R}^5</m>,
    so <m>n = 5</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
    <p>
    Find the value of <m>t</m> so that <m>\lambda = 3</m> is an eigenvalue
    of <m> \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp t \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 3
           \end{pmatrix} </m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
    <solution>
    <p>
    We use the cofactor expansion along the third row to solve:
    <m>0 = \det(A-3I)
    = \det \begin{pmatrix}
             -2 \amp t \amp 3 \\
             1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
             3 \amp 0 \amp 0
           \end{pmatrix}
    = 3(t+6),
    </m>
    so <m>t = -6</m>.
    </p>
    </solution>    

    <exercise workspace="2in">
    <statement>
     <p>
     Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix with characteristic
     polynomial <m>(1-\lambda)(2-\lambda).</m>  Find the characteristic
     polynomial of <m>A^2</m>.
     </p>
    </statement>
    </exercise>   
     <solution>
      <p>
      We observe that if <m>\lambda</m> is an eigenvalue for a square matrix
      <m>A</m>, then <m>\lambda^2</m> is an eigenvalue for <m>A^2</m>,
      since for any <m>\lambda</m>-eigenvector <m>v</m> of <m>A</m>:
      </p>
      <p>
      <m>A^2 v = A(Av) = A(\lambda v)= \lambda Av = \lambda(\lambda v)
      = \lambda^2 v.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
      Here, the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>\lambda = 1</m> and <m>\lambda = 2</m>,
      so the eigenvalues of <m>A^2</m> are <m>1^2 = 1</m> and <m>2^2 = 4</m>.
      These are the only possible eigenvalues of <m>A</m> since a <m>2 \times 2</m>
      matrix has at most <m>2</m> eigenvalues.  Therefore, the characteristic polynomial
      of <m>A^2</m> is <m>(1-\lambda)(4-\lambda)</m>.
      </p>
     </solution>    

     <exercise workspace="2in">
     <statement>
     <p>
     Suppose that <m>x</m> is an eigenvector of a matrix <m>A</m> corresponding
     to <m>\lambda = 3</m> and that <m>x</m> is also an eigenvector of a matrix
     <m>B</m> corresponding to <m>\lambda = 4</m>.
     </p>
     <p>
     Determine if <m>x</m> an eigenvector for <m>2A-B</m>.  If so, find the
     corresponding eigenvalue.
     </p>
     </statement>
     </exercise>   
     <solution>
     <p>
     We compute <m>(2A-B)(x) = 2Ax - Bx = 2(3x)-4x = 2x.</m>
     Therefore, <m>x</m> is an eigenvector of <m>2A-B</m> corresponding
     to the eigenvalue <m>\lambda = 2</m>.
     </p>
     </solution>     

     <exercise workspace="2in">
     <statement>
     <p>
     Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>4 \times 4</m> matrix with eigenvalues
     <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, and <m>2</m>, where the eigenvalue <m>1</m>
     has algebraic multiplicity <m>2</m>.  Which of the following statements
     must be true? Select all that apply.
     <ol>
     <li><m>A</m> is not invertible. </li>
     <li><m>A</m> is not diagonalizable. </li>
     </ol>
     </p>
     </statement>
     </exercise>   
     <solution>
     <p>
     <ol>
     <li>True: <m>A</m> is not invertible, since it has <m>\lambda = 0</m> as
     an eigenvalue. </li>
     <li>Not necessarily true.  it is possible for <m>A</m> to be diagonalizable, 
      for example
     <m>A =
     \begin{pmatrix}
       0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
       0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
       0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
       0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2
     \end{pmatrix}.
     </m>
     </li>
     </ol>
     </p>
     </solution>     

     <exercise workspace="2in">
     <statement>
     <p>
     True or false: Suppose <m>A</m> is a <m>5 \times 5</m> matrix with real
     entries.  Then <m>A</m> must have at least one real eigenvalue.
     </p>
     </statement>
     </exercise>   
     <solution>
     <p>
     True.  The characteristic polynomial of an <m>n \times n</m> matrix 
     <m>A</m> is a degree <m>n</m> polynomial whose coefficients are real
     numbers, and its roots (which occur in conjugate pairs)
     are the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>.
     </p>
     <p> This guarantees <m>A</m> has at least one real eigenvalue if <m>n</m> 
      is odd, which is the case here since <m>n=5</m>.
     </p>
     </solution>     
</worksheet>
